{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d5007e17-ede2-4ef0-9f96-2717003f4a16","content":"Here's the mapping from VSTest flags to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) equivalents. MTP-specific options go after `--`:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test \\\n  --filter \"Category=Integration\" \\\n  -- \\\n  --report-trx \\\n  --coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura \\\n  --crashdump \\\n  --hangdump --hangdump-timeout 5m\n```\n\n**Required NuGet packages** (add to your test project):\n\n| Package | Enables |\n|---|---|\n| `Microsoft.Testing.Platform.MSBuild` | `dotnet test` integration with MTP |\n| `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` | `--report-trx` |\n| `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage` | `--coverage` |\n| `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CrashDump` | `--crashdump` |\n| `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HangDump` | `--hangdump` |\n\n**Key differences:**\n- `--logger trx` → `--report-trx`\n- `--collect \"Code Coverage;…\"` → `--coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura`\n- `--blame-crash` → `--crashdump`\n- `--blame-hang --blame-hang-timeout` → `--hangdump --hangdump-timeout`\n- `--filter` stays the same (translated by the MSBuild integration layer)","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e4bde8a2-e5b1-4fa8-9dc4-bbd5c5eac318","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating their CI test command from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) on .NET 8. This is a knowledge question about .NET testing tooling - I can answer this directly without needing to explore any codebase.\n\nLet me map each VSTest flag to its MTP equivalent:\n\n1. `dotnet test` → `dotnet test` (still works, but MTP uses different CLI args)\n2. `--filter \"Category=Integration\"` → `--filter \"Category=Integration\"` (same in MTP via `--filter`)\n3. `--logger trx` → `--report-trx` (MTP built-in)\n\n\n4. `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` → `--coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura` (MTP's native coverage approach with Microsoft.CodeCoverage)\n5. `--blame-crash` → `--crashdump` (MTP equivalent)\n6. `--blame-hang` → `--hangdump` (MTP equivalent)\n7. `--blame-hang-timeout 5m` → `--hangdump-timeout 5m` (MTP equivalent)\n\nI'm realizing there's an important distinction here - MTP has two different execution modes, and the CLI arguments differ depending on whether you're using `dotnet test` as a wrapper or running the test host directly.\n\nOn .NET 8, if you want to use MTP with `dotnet test`, you need to enable it in the project file with `<TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>` or add the MSBuild package. Otherwise, you're still going through VSTest. With .NET 9 SDK, MTP support is built in natively. The alternative is to build the test project and invoke the executable directly, which gives you full access to MTP's command-line interface. The newer MTP packages provide their own command-line arguments that replace the old VSTest ones—things like `--report-trx` for tracing, `--coverage` with format options for code coverage, and `--crashdump`/`--hangdump` for diagnostic collection. When using `dotnet test` with MTP integration through MSBuild, some of the legacy VSTest arguments get translated automatically, but the user likely wants to know the proper native MTP syntax for these operations. The cleanest approach is to run `dotnet test` with MTP-specific flags after `--`, and you'll need several NuGet packages to enable each feature: `Microsoft.Testing.Platform.MSBuild` for the integration layer, `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` for test result reporting, `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage` for coverage collection, `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CrashDump` for crash dumps, and `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HangDump` for hang detection.","outputTokens":1671,"requestId":"3405:1A5086:760774D:825C3AF:69F3FB6D"},"id":"ec48329d-a282-4eaa-a37c-22888aee9e5e","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:02:01.258Z","parentId":"6c329a3b-2da4-40da-87ce-3ff595d9e2db"}
